These works take, hours, weeks, sometimes even years to complete. My process involves meticulous layering of details, linework, gestural markmaking, and mixing of materials. They are valued based on time, and I generally keep the value consistent for my collectors. Occasionally I mark a few originals down like a treasure hunt for the lucky collector!

"Alienana" is made with watercolor, pen and ink, paint marker, metallic ink on 9"x12" paper. 2018. Hunt for this treasure, and a few more in the "watercolor" section!

“Chronic Pain Survivor” slide for full painting. In a lot of pain lately, which makes drawing and painting very difficult and a real challenge. I accept. I find a way to push through and create every day, despite the pain. I finished this piece last night. This work is honest about my current feelings and physical state. I don’t always post this kind of work here since the algorithm favors more colorful work and more uplifting subject matter. I think it is important for artists to show different styles of work and break free from the control of the algorithm. Let’s see how this one does! Slide to see the full piece and more details.

Hi everyone, Jadda Cat here, posting for Mike while he is recovering. The surgery went well today, and he's now in the recovery room. I'm still waiting to see him! Thank you all for your positive vibes ❤ I'll give him a big hug from you all when he gets out!

This highly detailed painting on paper took months to create. Look closely to see all the creatures and body parts made with layers of mixed media ink, oil stick, paint marker, gouache, collaged drawings, and so much more! This is a style that Mike has developed since he was a child. I don't think even he would be able to tell you how exactly it was made. 

#artonpaper #artadventure #contemporaryartist #contemporarydrawing #contemporarypainting #oilsticks #inkart #figurativeart #flamingabstracts #flaming_abstracts #artstyle #artstyle

I quickly drew this clock before they put me under. As a mental choice to draw before my surgery (filled the book) as a symbol of hope and resilience. Art to me is life. It's my voice To inspire. Taking pain and transferring it into hope. So many people are struggling as well as me, but with art and strong will we can push on beyond the hill and make art to change hearts and minds!! So many people ask me what is my goal, my goal is to live and create art that goes beyond need and want and be that alien that makes art work that hits people! #healthcare #artist #painter #nycartist #fineart #drawing #advocate #artist #clocks #dvt #nycpainter #hope #pushon #ink #doodle #fun #drawings #painter #contemporaryartist #artheals #healing #pma #chelseanyc #nyny #kindness (if you struggling pick up that pen and let it out ) #healthcareforall #positivevibes #healthylifestyle #contemporarypainting #arte #artcollector #artlover

“Surreal-a-thon” Been working on this piece forever! It took at least 20 hours to complete. This represents a very fun time in my life. A portrait of my friend Dave RIP. He didn’t take anything seriously. Remembering the moment when he put a Reese’s wrapper on his face, an orange juice box on his head, and chocolate covered eyeballs on his ears and modeled for everyone to draw. Life is short. Live silly.

“Alan’s thread-like lines are manically impulsive; they barely go an inch without detouring. Short, jagged strokes, tiny loops, and quick arcs make jittery, skeletal outlines of distorted human forms. Hasty daubs of blues and pinks wrap the frames with translucent skin while also conveying the blur of movement. Alan loves motion; in Move in Distance, a dancer’s five legs, kicking up in successive positions, pay homage to those futurist studies in dynamism. Even the reclining male figure...looks restless—the angular, attenuated limbs and their busy surfaces bring to mind one of Egon Schiele’s more anxious self-portraits.”
Robert Shuster, The Village Voice, Best in Show
